def extract_zip_to_memory(input_zip):
    '''
    This function extracts the images stored inside the given zip file.
    It stores the result in a python dictionary.
    
    input_zip (string): path to the zip file
    
    returns (dict): {filename (string): image_file (bytes)}
    '''
    input_zip=zipfile.ZipFile(input_zip)
    return {name: BytesIO(input_zip.read(name)) for name in input_zip.namelist() if name.endswith('.jpg')}

# Load the image as a numpy array:
# np_arr = np.array(Image.open(img_files['imgs/32738710.jpg']))

# Be aware that the dictionary will occupy roughly 2GB of computer memory!
# To free this memory again, run:
# del img_files

#Recall, precision and F1-score, the metrics that interest us

def recall_m(y_true, y_pred):
    true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
    possible_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true, 0, 1)))
    recall = true_positives / (possible_positives + K.epsilon())
    return recall

def precision_m(y_true, y_pred):
    true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
    predicted_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_pred, 0, 1)))
    precision = true_positives / (predicted_positives + K.epsilon())
    return precision

def f1_m(y_true, y_pred):
    precision = precision_m(y_true, y_pred)
    recall = recall_m(y_true, y_pred)
    return 2*((precision*recall)/(precision+recall+K.epsilon()))

##Function to build the CNN for different activation functions

def build_CNN(learning_rate ,dropout, x_train , y_train , x_test , y_test , epochs , batch_size):
    CNN = Sequential()
    CNN.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3),
                     activation='relu',
                     input_shape=(87, 67, 1)))
    CNN.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    CNN.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), 
                     activation='relu'))
    CNN.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    CNN.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), 
                     activation='relu'))
    CNN.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    CNN.add(Flatten())  # this converts our 3D feature maps to 1D feature vectors
    CNN.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    CNN.add(Dropout(dropout))
    CNN.add(Dense(39, activation='softmax'))


    CNN.compile(loss=keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy,
              optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adadelta(lr = learning_rate),
              metrics=[f1_m,precision_m,recall_m])
    
    
    CNN.summary()

    history = CNN.fit(x_train, y_train,
              batch_size=batch_size,
              epochs=epochs,
              verbose=1,
              validation_data=(x_test, y_test))
    
    return(CNN)

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    Goal : This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')
        
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (30,30))

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()

    #Adding a three new lines in our df (one for each modification) with the unique_name corresponding to the original image
    df = pd.DataFrame({'objid' :[j,j+1,j+2,j+3], 'level2' :[specie , specie ,specie ,specie]})
    img_info_aug = img_info_aug.append(df, ignore_index=True)  
    j+=4


for i in range (j):
  img = np.array(img_arrays[i])
  #img = np.divide((img),255)
  #img = img.astype('float16')
  images.append(color.gray2rgb(img))


  label_encoded = np.zeros(shape=( 1, len(label_name)))
  label_encoded[0][np.argwhere(label_name==img_info_aug.loc[img_info_aug['objid'] == i, 'level2'].values[0])[0][0]] = 1
  labels.append(label_encoded[0])

del img_arrays
        
end = time()
duration = end - start
print('Execution time: {}minutes'.format(duration/60))

Working on features¶

Data exploration: features exploitation approach¶

In addition to the images, the meta.csv file containing metadata about the images, and the taxo.csv file defining the taxonomy tree we have two other csv files.

  • features_native.csv.gz contains the morphological handcrafted features computed by ZooProcess. In fact, ZooProcess generates the region of interests (ROI) around each individual object from a original image of Plankton. In addition, it also computes a set of associated features measured on the object. These features are the ones contained in features_native.csv.gz

  • features_skimage.csv.gz contains the morphological features recomputed with skimage.measure.regionprops on the ROIs produced by ZooProcess.

These two files contain information extracted from the images in form of features. This ZooProcess method is a software developped by an engineer from the Laboratoire d’Océanologie de Villefranche sur mer. During the next cells, we will try to explore and process these two files, in order to apply directly learning methods.

Model selection: features approach¶

Here, we define a function using a cross-validation strategy, in order to validate more accurately our models. Using KFold and shuffling(cross-validation) and using cross_val_score with the right scoring.

In [0]:
#Validation function
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score

n_folds = 5

def f1_cv(model, X, y):
    kf = KFold(n_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42).get_n_splits(X)
    f1 = cross_val_score(model, X, y, scoring="f1_macro", cv = kf)
    return(f1)

#optimizing the parameter k
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve

neighbors = [x for x in range(1,20)]

train_results = []

for n in neighbors:
  start= time.time()
  knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n)
  knn.fit(X_features_10p_train, y_features_10p_train)
  train_pred = knn.predict(X_features_10p_train)
  #print(classification_report(y_features_10p_train, train_pred))
  train_results.append(np.mean(f1_cv(knn, X_features_10p_train, y_features_10p_train)))
  end = time.time()
  print(end - start)
  print(n)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
plt.plot(neighbors, train_results)
plt.ylabel('F1 CV')
plt.xlabel('neighbors')
plt.show()

# Number of trees in random forest

# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 6)]
max_depth.append(None)
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf}

Performance evaluation¶

First as we compare the features approach to the images approach we can notice that we have pretty bad results on the features approach. Moreover we have issues with the understanding of the feature while in the images approach we feel more confident about what is happening and what criteria makes the classification. So we decided to choose the side of the images approach.

Secondly, according to the lack of time we had to fully train a CNN from scratch we decided to go along with the pre-trained VGG16 CNN model.
